'''Michael C. Moynihan''' is an [[United States|American]] [[journalist]]. He is a [[senior editor]] of the [[libertarian]] magazine ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]''. Moynihan founded the [[English language]] magazine based in [[Stockholm, Sweden]], the ''Stockholm Spectator''. He was a resident fellow of the [[free-market]] [[think tank]], [[Timbro]]. Moynihan lived in [[Sweden]] and wrote articles about the politics in the country, contributing to [[Swedish language]] publications, including ''[[Expressen]]'', ''[[Aftonbladet]]'', ''[[Sveriges Television]]'', ''[[Neo (magazine)|Neo]]'', and ''[[G<U+00F6>teborgs-Tidningen]]''. 

He became associate editor at ''Reason'' in 2007, and was a contributor to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' in 2008. In 2009 one of his articles for ''Reason'' was cited in ''The Georgetown Journal of Law & Public Policy'' of the [[Georgetown University Law Center]]. Moynihan appeared as a commentator multiple times on the television program ''[[Glenn Beck (TV program)|Glenn Beck]]'' on the [[Fox News Channel]] in 2009. After [[censorship]] of by [[Comedy Central]] of an episode of ''[[South Park]]'' in 2010 that featured a depiction of the Prophet of [[Islam]], [[Muhammad]], Moynihan announced his support for the protest movement, "[[Everybody Draw Mohammed Day]]".

==Education==
Moynihan graduated from the [[University of Massachusetts]], with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[history]].<ref name="bio">{{cite news | title = Staff: Michael C. Moynihan - Reason Magazine | work = [[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] | language =  | publisher =reason.com  | date =2010  | url = http://reason.com/people/michael-c-moynihan/articles | accessdate = 2010-05-06 }}</ref>

==Career==
===Sweden===
Moynihan is the founder of the [[English language]] magazine based in [[Stockholm, Sweden]], the ''Stockholm Spectator''.<ref name="uddenfeldt">{{cite news| last = Uddenfeldt  | first =  Therese | title = Stockholm kan f<U+00E5> tidning p<U+00E5> engelska | work = [[Sveriges Radio]] | language =  | publisher = sverigesradio.se | date =July 27, 2004  | url =  http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=478&artikel=449066| accessdate = 2010-05-06 }}</ref> The ''Stockholm Spectator'' was modeled after the [[New York]] publication, ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref name="uddenfeldt" /> Writers were mainly English-speaking [[ex-patriot]]s living in Sweden, and the publication began with a [[Magazine circulation|circulation]] of 10,000 copies.<ref name="uddenfeldt" /> Moynihan got the idea for the magazine after spending time in [[Prague]] and [[Copenhagen]]; both cities that had English-language publications.<ref name="uddenfeldt" /> He started the ''Stockholm Spectator'' with his girlfriend.<ref name="uddenfeldt" /> "Despite the fact that so many Swedes speak and read in English there were almost no English-language newspapers in Sweden," said Moynihan to ''[[Sveriges Radio]]''.<ref name="uddenfeldt" /> The publication first began online, at www.spectator.se.<ref name="uddenfeldt" /> It maintained a focus on criticism of the media, but also dealt with current topics in politics and music.<ref name="uddenfeldt" /> Moynihan served on the [[editorial board]] of the Swedish newspaper ''Neo'' in 2006 along with Peter Wolodarski and Theodore Paues; and Swedish politician [[Carl Bildt]] sat on the board of the publication.<ref>{{cite news| last = Ekstr<U+00F6>m | first = Andreas | title =Borgerlighet f<U+00F6>r "gr<U+00E4>stoppar"  | work = Sydsvenskan  | language =  | publisher = www.sydsvenskan.se | date =January 18, 2006  | url =  http://www.sydsvenskan.se/samtidigt/article136723/Borgerlighet-for-grastoppar.html| accessdate = 2010-05-06 }}</ref>

During a controversy in 2006 where the website [[SD-Kuriren]] was criticized by the [[Swedish Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Laila Freivalds]] for publishing satires of the Prophet [[Muhammad]] of [[Islam]], the website was taken down by its provider.<ref name="goldenberg">{{cite news| last = Goldenberg | first = David | coauthors =  | title =Condom Nation: Gelf highlights overlooked coverage from local media around the world. In this edition: A prophylactic push; a defiant editor; and a lot of missing teeth.  | work = Gelf Magazine | publisher = www.gelfmagazine.com | page =  | date = February 16, 2006 | url = http://www.gelfmagazine.com/archives/condom_nation.php | accessdate = 2010-05-06 }}</ref> As editor of the ''Stockholm Spectator'', Moynihan reacted to what he viewed as suppression of [[freedom of the press]], and posted to the blog of the magazine one of the more offensive of the caricatures of Muhammad.<ref name="goldenberg" /> He served as a resident fellow at the organization [[Timbro]], a [[free-market]] [[think tank]] based in Stockholm.<ref name="bio" /><ref>{{cite news| last =  Moynihan| first = Michael | title =Stockholm Syndrome  | work = The American | publisher =  [[American Enterprise Institute]] | date = October 4, 2007 | url =  http://www.american.com/archive/2007/october-10-07/stockholm-syndrome| accessdate =2010-05-06  }}</ref> He lived in [[Sweden]] and wrote articles about the politics in the country.<ref name="mcardle">{{cite news| last = McArdle  | first = Megan  | title =Sweden: paradise or purgatory?  | work = The Atlantic | publisher =www.theatlantic.com | date = June 5, 2008 | url =http://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2008/06/sweden-paradise-or-purgatory/3618/  | accessdate =2010-05-06  }}</ref> Moynihan has contributed articles to [[Swedish language]] publications, including ''[[Expressen]]'', ''[[Aftonbladet]]'', ''[[Sveriges Television]]'', ''[[Neo (magazine)|Neo]]'', and ''[[G<U+00F6>teborgs-Tidningen]]''.<ref name="bio" /> Moynihan was the [[Film producer|producer]] of a 2006 [[documentary]] for [[Modern Times Group]] of [[Sweden]]'s ''[[TV8 (Sweden)|TV8]]'', on American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]  radio [[talk show]] host [[Barry Farber]].<ref name="bio" /> He performed research for Timbro in 2007 in which he wrote critically of [[Noam Chomsky]]'s research methods, and argued that Chomsky did not deserve an [[honorary doctorate]] he received at [[Uppsala University]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Timbro tar heder och <U+00E4>ra av Noam Chomsky  | work = [[Hufvudstadsbladet]] | language =  | publisher = Hufvudstadsbladet, Finland | page = 25 | date =May 30, 2007 }}</ref> 
===Washington, D.C.===
Moynihan was an associate editor for ''Reason'' prior to serving as its senior editor,<ref>{{cite news | title =Michael Moore schticko | work =[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|location=[[Chicago, Illinois]] | page = B5 | date =  July 1, 2007  }}</ref> having joined the staff of the magazine in August 2007.<ref>{{cite news  | title =Reason news  | work =[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] | date = August 1, 2007 | url = http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-6755085/reason-news-Letters-Public-notice.html | accessdate =  2010-05-06}}</ref> His December 24, 2007 article for ''Reason'', "Flunking Free Speech: The Persistent Threat to Liberty on College Campuses" was cited by Robert H. Jackson Legal Fellow at the [[Foundation for Individual Rights in Education]], Azhar Majeed, in the [[legal journal]] ''The Georgetown Journal of Law & Public Policy'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite news| last =  Majeed  | first =Azhar | coauthors =  | title =  Defying the Constitution The Rise, Persistence, And Prevalence Of Campus Speech Codes| work = The Georgetown Journal of Law & Public Policy | publisher = [[Georgetown University Law Center]] | page = 7 Geo. J.L. & Pub. Pol'y 481 | date =  Summer 2009 }}</ref> Moynihan was a contributor to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite news| last =  Meier | first =Andrew|coauthors=Michael C. Moynihan | title = Can the civilized world civilize Russia? | work =[[Los Angeles Times]] | publisher = www.latimes.com | date =  August 27, 2008| url = http://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/suncommentary/la-oew-meier-moynihan27-2008aug27,0,1032432.story?page=2 | accessdate = 2010-05-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last =Moynihan  | first = Michael C. | coauthors =  Andrew Meier| title = Is NATO reaching too far east? | work =[[Los Angeles Times]] | publisher = www.latimes.com | date =August 26, 2008  | url = http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/la-oew-meier-moynihan26-2008aug26%2C0%2C4404939%2Cfull.story | accessdate =2010-05-06 }}</ref> After [[Barack Obama]] was elected [[President of the United States]] in November 2008, ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' highlighted critical comments by Moynihan of the [[President-Elect]]'s supporters, in a sample of political viewpoints following the election.<ref>{{cite news| last =  | first =  | coauthors =  | title =Election 2008: The presidency: The Voices: 'A great day for all of us': Free coffee and monumental change: Here's an Election Day sampling of political (and other) blog comments on voting, domestic policy, the candidates and two interesting parallels.  | work =[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]]  | page =  pEX2| date =November 5, 2008 }}</ref> He conducted interviews for ''Reason.tv'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite news| title = Video: Tea Party Confidential: Taxpayer March on Washington | work =The Trentonian | publisher = www.trentonian.com | date = September 15, 2009 | url =http://www.trentonian.com/articles/2009/09/15/opinion/doc4aaffd0e83d54950233344.txt  | accessdate = 2010-05-06 }}</ref> Moynihan appeared multiple times as a guest on the ''[[Glenn Beck (TV program)|Glenn Beck]]'' television program on [[Fox News Channel]]; in March,<ref name="shouldgovernment" /> April,<ref>{{cite news| last = Beck | first =Glenn|authorlink=Glenn Beck | title = BECK for April 14, 2009| work = [[Glenn Beck (TV program)|Glenn Beck]]  | publisher = [[Fox News Channel]] | date = April 14, 2009  }}</ref> and May 2009.<ref>{{cite news| last = Gutfeld   | first = Greg |authorlink=Greg Gutfeld| coauthors =Andrew Napolitano  | title =  BECK for May 20, 2009| work = [[Glenn Beck (TV program)|Glenn Beck]] | publisher =[[Fox News Channel]] | date = May 20, 2009 }}</ref> In 2010, he was a visiting fellow at Timbro.<ref name="bio" /> Moynihan is the senior editor of both ''Reason'' magazine, as well as its website, Reason.com.<ref name="shouldgovernment">{{cite news | title = Should Government Bail Out Newspapers? | work =[[Fox News Channel]] | publisher = FOX News Network, LLC. | date =  March 18, 2009| url =  http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,509696,00.html| accessdate =2010-05-06  }}</ref><ref name="bio" /> He resided in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 2010.<ref name="bio" />

Moynihan announced his participation in the protest movement "[[Everybody Draw Mohammed Day]]" which began in May 2010.<ref name="erases">{{cite news | title = Cartoonist Molly Norris Erases 'Draw Muhammad' Gag | work = [[FOX 9]] | publisher =  Fox Television Stations, Inc. | date =April 26, 2010  | url = http://www.myfoxtwincities.com/dpps/news/cartoonist-molly-norris-draw-muhammad-gag-dpgoha-20100426-fc_7252284 | accessdate = 2010-05-06 }}</ref> The movement grew in response to [[censorship]] by [[Comedy Central]] of an episode of ''[[South Park]]'' which depicted the Prophet Muhammad.<ref name="erases" /> Moynihan stated he would post his own contributions in addition to submissions from other individuals to the website of ''Reason'' on the protest movement's scheduled date of May 20, 2010.<ref name="erases" /> He encouraged his readers to send him their drawings.<ref name="moynihan423">{{cite news| last = Moynihan | first = Michael C. | title = First Annual Everybody Draw Mohammad Day | work = Hit and Run | publisher =[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] | date = April 23, 2010 | url = http://reason.com/blog/2010/04/23/first-annual-everybody-draw-mo | accessdate = 2010-04-27 }}</ref> Moynihan stated he planned to select some of his favorite depictions of Muhammad from the protest movement, and then add them to the Reason.com website.<ref name="moye" /><ref name="moynihan423" /> Moynihan commented, "In the South Park episode that started all this, Buddha does lines of coke and there was an episode where Cartman started a Christian rock band that sang very homo-erotic songs. Yet there is one religious figure we can't make fun of. The point of the episode that started the controversy is that celebrities wanted Muhammad's power not to be ridiculed. How come non-Muslims aren't allowed to make jokes?"<ref name="moye" /> Moynihan noted, "Any time you cave into terrorism, it emboldens extremists," and posited that the decision of Comedy Central to enact [[self-censorship]] of the ''South Park'' episode would have the impact of worsening the situation.<ref name="moye">{{cite news| last = Moye | first = Dan | title = Creators Out, But Muhammad Drawing Protest Is On | work =[[AOL News]]  | publisher =[[AOL]] | date = April 27, 2010 | url = http://www.aolnews.com/weird-news/article/creators-back-out-but-muhammad-drawing-protest-continues/19455021 | accessdate = May 2, 2010 }}</ref>

